{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-topic-topic-tsx","path":"/topics/support-for-adult-carers/","result":{"data":{"firstChapter":{"id":"c8031010-eeca-5ec2-8a2b-5fb3ca2eb166","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[],"depth":1,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 183be427-4791-4b4e-abb0-ac4000b1e436 --><h1>Support for adult carers: Summary</h1><!-- end field 183be427-4791-4b4e-abb0-ac4000b1e436 -->","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 8888e7a8-f9f6-49ed-815a-ac4000b1e436 --><!-- begin field 9d998d74-adf5-4d9a-a8fa-ac4000b1e436 --><ul><li>An adult carer provides unpaid care and support to a family member, partner, or friend, because of health or social care needs that can include a disability, health condition, mental health problem, frailty, or addiction.<ul><li>The caring role varies between carers and differs depending on the needs of the person being cared for, but may include domestic tasks, help with mobility, help with washing and dressing, childcare, emotional support, and help with financial matters.</li></ul></li><li>It is estimated that there are seven million unpaid carers in the UK. At some time in their life, 3 in 5 people will be a carer.</li><li>Carers make a valuable contribution to the people for whom they care, and to society.<ul><li>There are rewarding, positive, and beneficial aspects of a caring role, but the challenges of caring can include impact on physical and mental health; social effects (for example social isolation and loneliness); financial difficulties; and impact on work and employment.</li></ul></li><li>If carers are not identified, it is a barrier to them receiving appropriate support. Opportunities such as GP appointments should be used to actively seek to identify carers.<ul><li>Some people might not view themselves as a carer, or may not ask for support from certain professionals because they may not view support for carers as part of that professional's role.</li></ul></li><li>Carers should be offered the opportunity to confidentially discuss their own needs as carers (separately from the person they are supporting) and it should be ensured carers know about their right to have a carer's assessment.</li><li>Carers should be made aware of their right to information and support and how to access it.</li><li>Supporting carers in their caring role should include:<ul><li>Encouraging carers to recognize their caring role and seek support.</li><li>Involving carers in decision-making and care planning for the person they care for (with the consent of the person being cared for).</li><li>Offering carers ongoing contact and support and training.</li><li>Providing information and emotional and practical support when a carer's circumstances change, or to help them prepare for changes.</li><li>Discussing work, if relevant, in relation to their caring role.</li><li>Offering practical support such as flexible appointment times and longer appointments.</li></ul></li><li>Ways that carers' wellbeing can be supported include:<ul><li>Helping them access healthcare for themselves.</li><li>Addressing carers' health needs as soon as possible.</li><li>Discussing the value of breaks from the caring role.</li><li>Providing information and emotional and practical support when a carer's circumstances change, or to help them prepare for changes.</li><li>Considering providing psychosocial and psychoeducational support.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 9d998d74-adf5-4d9a-a8fa-ac4000b1e436 --><!-- end item 8888e7a8-f9f6-49ed-815a-ac4000b1e436 -->","topic":{"id":"8a0dcd0d-457e-51f3-bb8d-cb9abed98985","topicId":"535a2cb2-ac55-4c42-ba32-ac4000b1d290","topicName":"Support for adult carers","slug":"support-for-adult-carers","aliases":[],"chapters":[{"id":"c8031010-eeca-5ec2-8a2b-5fb3ca2eb166","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"69ec7c8f-cf0d-5dbd-b893-89c2650a72ca","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","subChapters":[]},{"id":"4